# Companion for Linux

This download contains two builds:

- Desktop - has a graphical interface, launched with `companion-launcher`
- Standalone headless - no graphical interface, launched with `./companion_headless.sh` (for servers and embedded use)

Below are the setup steps for each. Section 4 (dependencies) and section 5 (udev / USB permissions) apply to both.

---

1. Headless install (recommended for servers)

   If you want to run Companion on a headless machine, we recommend using the CompanionPi install script:

   $ curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bitfocus/companion-pi/main/install.sh | bash

   It sets everything up for you: system dependencies, a `companion` user and group, the udev rules, and an easy update script. It works on Debian and Ubuntu based systems, on both x64 and arm64.

   If you'd rather set things up yourself, use the standalone headless build in section 3.

2. Desktop install

   Extract the download and run `companion-launcher`.

   Before USB surfaces (Stream Decks, Loupedecks, X-keys, etc.) will work, you need the udev rules from section 5 installed. You currently need to perform this manually, they get generated for you into your config folder $HOME/.config/companion-nodejs/udev-rules/

   If launching fails with "Using GTK 2/3 and GTK 4 in the same process is not supported", append the argument: --gtk-version=3

3. Standalone headless build

   The `./companion_headless.sh` script in this download starts the standalone headless build - Companion without the graphical interface. This is supported, but is not recommended - you must perform the dependency, group and udev setup (sections 4 and 5) yourself, and you get none of the automation the install script in section 1 provides. Prefer the install script unless you have a specific reason not to.

   You'll typically want to define a systemd unit to launch it however you wish. For examples, see the scripts in the CompanionPi repository:
   https://github.com/bitfocus/companion-pi#other-debianubuntu

4. Required dependencies

   Companion requires some dependencies that aren't included by default on some Debian and Ubuntu installations:

   $ apt-get update
   $ apt-get install -y libusb-1.0-0-dev libudev-dev libfontconfig1

5. Udev rules (USB permissions)

   For Companion to access your Stream Decks, Loupedecks, X-keys and other supported USB surfaces, some udev rules must be installed into /etc/udev/rules.d/.

   Since Companion 4.3, surfaces are integrated through modules, so we cannot ship a fixed udev rules file - the required USB device ids change as you enable and disable surface modules. Instead, Companion generates the rules on the fly into its config folder (in the `udev-rules` directory) and keeps them up to date as modules change.

   There are two generated files, for the two ways of running:
   - 50-companion-desktop.rules - for the desktop build. Uses udev's `uaccess` tag, so the logged-in graphical user is granted access automatically. No special group is needed.
   - 50-companion-headless.rules - for the headless build. Grants access to a group called `companion`, so Companion must be run as a member of that group (this is what the install script sets up).

   To apply the rules for your build, copy the matching file into /etc/udev/rules.d/ and reload:
   $ udevadm control --reload-rules
   $ udevadm trigger
   then replug any USB devices Companion should use.

   You need to repeat this whenever the generated file changes (i.e. after enabling or disabling a surface module).

   Automating this:
   - Desktop: Not yet supported
   - Headless: set the environment variable COMPANION_SYNC_UDEV_RULES_COMMAND to a command that installs and reloads the rules, and Companion will run it automatically whenever the rules change. The install script in section 1 configures this for you.
